  "prompt": "Why do people buy overpriced stocks?",
  "response": "People buy overpriced stocks for various reasons:\n\n1. Speculation\n- Believing the price will continue to rise\n- Hoping to sell at an even higher price\n- Expecting future growth potential\n\n2. FOMO (Fear of Missing Out)\n- Seeing others making money\n- Feeling pressure to join the trend\n- Emotional decision-making\n\n3. Perceived value\n- Believing the stock is undervalued\n- Trusting company's future prospects\n- Confidence in management or industry\n\n4. Momentum investing\n- Stocks trending upward\n- Technical analysis signals\n- Riding the wave of market excitement\n\n5. Limited understanding\n- Lack of financial knowledge\n- Not fully analyzing stock fundamentals\n- Following recommendations without research\n\n6. Media and hype\n- Positive news coverage\n- Influential analyst recommendations\n- Social media buzz\n\n7. Psychological biases\n- Confirmation bias\n- Overconfidence\n- Herding mentality\n\n8. Long-term investment strategy\n- Believing in company's long-term potential\n- Willing to overlook short-term overvaluation\n\n9. Portfolio diversification\n- Adding different stocks for balance\n- Spreading investment risk\n\nWhile these reasons exist, experts generally advise thorough research and rational decision-making when investing.",
